         <TR BGCOLOR="#000000"><Td ALIGN="LEFT">
         <FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana" COLOR="#c0c0c0">
         <blockquote>
         "I'm not following you on a class system with an easily attainable max leading to a situation of no different CLASSES."<P>Becasue you read it wrong.  I said that MULTICLASSING in NWN/DSO lead to all pvpers having the same skill set.  Everyone in NWN was a 14/15 Cleric/Mage.   Nearly everyone in UO was a GM mage, GM resist, GM enter your melee weapon of choice here.  Everyone in DSO was 14/14/15 Druid/Psionic/Preserver. <P>All the good PvP games to date (NWN, DSO, Old UO) had a system where you variance in skills was minimal.<P>The class system fails to provide quality PvP because PvP is Player vs Player not Character vs Character.  Class systems tend to create an imbalance where one class will always win over the other given a specific circumstance.   A warrior will always beat an archer in an enclosed area.  An archer will always beat a melee when the battle starts at a distance in an open area, a wizard who is out of mana will die to a melee that's half his level, and so on.  You have a game of rock, paper, scissors where you are always the rock.<P>Dont get me wrong (you keep trying to) I like it when there are character releated issues that will effect the outcome of the fight.   Did you bring enough arrows?  Do you have potions, wands, scrolls?  Did you choose the right spells?  Do you have an escape route? Did you buff?  Are you wearing the right resist gear?  These are all decisions made by the player and any mistakes can learned from for the next fight, they are not limitations forced on the player by a decision he made 12 months and 20 game altering patches ago.   They also dont guarentee the outcome of the fight, just tip the balance a bit.<P>After reading the SB FAQ I said to myself,  "Play a dwarf warrior and you will die to centuar archers all day, everyday no matter how good you are. Now there's a balanced PvP game if I ever heard of one."<P>
         </blockquote>
